<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-453-579  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 453 579.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Sept 17 1990 v4 n34 p26(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>FMS, GAO clash over OMB role in System 90. (Department ofTreasury's Financial Management Service, General AccountingOffice, Office of Management and Budget)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Richardson, Jennifer.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A dispute involving the Treasury Department's Financial ManagementService and the General Accounting Office's interpretation of theOffice of Management and Budget's rules on financial managementsystems has left some doubt as to which department has control oroversight of the Treasury's proposed System 90.andP;  The $48.8 millionSystem 90 contract, awarded last month to Computer Sciences Corp,is an integrated financial management system.andP;  The firstapplication, Payments, Claims and Enhanced Reconciliation system(PACER), is to be developed by the mid-1990s.andP;  Under CircularA-127 of the OMB's rules, all agencies must submit financialestimates and information associated with systems in the form of afive year plan.andP;  FMS claims this rule only applies to accountingsystems and, therefore, does not include either System 90 orPACER.andP;  OMB maintains that it applies to all systems containingfinancial data.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Government AgencyGovernment RegulationUnited States. General Accounting OfficeUnited States. Department of the Treasury. Financial ManagementServiceUnited States. Office of Management and BudgetGovernment FundingManagement Style.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>